equation_narrative.headline: N-terminal position encoding drives early polar signal, late Q-specific channels secure prediction
equation_narrative.story: Position 2 in ubiquitin sits immediately after the initiating methionine, creating a strong N-terminal context that dominates early processing. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with polar/charged residues, reading 7 structural contacts and 4 co-evolving positions. The logit lens shows volatile shifts between small polar residues (S, N, T) and charged residues (K, H) as the representation refines, but these reflect evolving context encoding rather than predictions. At layer 28, Q emerges as the clear winner when MLP neurons and attention heads activate Q-specific prediction channels, rising from 7% to 88% by layer 33.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a representation of the N-terminal biochemical environment. Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 at 44+ projection) encode positional context—this is the second residue after the start methionine. The model reads 7 structural contacts and 4 co-evolving positions, with attention heads showing predominantly local focus (L11 H2 erases with -1.91 projection, diffuse attention pattern). The logit lens trajectory is highly volatile, with lead changes at nearly every layer (S→H→N→A→S→A→K through L14), reflecting the model's refinement of what kind of residue belongs here rather than committing to a specific answer. By layer 18, features like F18:1374 and F18:5480 (11-12 projection) encode a polar/charged character consistent with the N-terminal exposed environment.
perception_phase.context_character: N-terminal exposed position with polar/charged character. The representation encodes proximity to the initiating methionine and surface-exposed environment, with moderate structural contacts (7 residues) and evolutionary coupling to 4 positions suggesting functional constraints on this early position.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 7 residues within contact distance, creating moderate burial context
Co-evolutionary signal: 4 coupled positions indicating functional constraints on N-terminal region
N-terminal position encoding: F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 (44+ projection) encode second-position context after start methionine
Local sequence reading: L25 H16 writes +2.45 projection with 96% local attention, integrating immediate neighbors M[?]IFVKT

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between layers 28-33. At L28, Q first takes the lead at 17.8%, overtaking L (17.5%). Layer 29 shows massive MLP activity with -5.39 total projection but strong Q-specific writers (N29:3536 at +0.81, N29:754 at +0.70). Layers 30-33 activate high-specificity Q prediction channels: F30:7134 (48.4 projection, attention), F33:324 (110.9 projection, MLP), and N32:3894 (+1.38 projection voting purely for Q). Q rises from 26% at L29 to 88% at L33, while competitor E peaks at 11% (L30) then fades to 5%.
decision_phase.transition: Layer 23 marks the perception-to-decision boundary. Through L23, the logit lens shows K leading at 31% with volatile competition from T, S, A—reflecting the model's refined but uncommitted representation of N-terminal polar/charged context. At L24, attention features shift dramatically (F24:6298 at 19.3 projection, F24:217 at 16.7) and MLP neurons begin casting AA-specific votes, though still with negative net projection (-0.3). By L25, Q-preferring neurons activate (N25:4987 at +0.71 for Q/K) and the representation transitions from 'what context is here' to 'Q should go here.'

candidates.narrative: Q emerges decisively in the decision phase after being nearly invisible through L27 (under 8% in logit lens). At L28, Q takes the lead for the first time at 17.8%. Layer 29 MLP neurons provide strong support despite net negative projection (N29:3536 +0.81, N29:754 +0.70, N29:4425 +0.55). Layers 30-33 activate highly specific Q prediction channels: F30:7134 (48.4 projection, attention), F33:324 (110.9 projection, MLP—the single strongest feature), and N32:3894 (+1.38 projection with Q as top vote). Q rises from 26% at L29 to 88% at L33, securing a confident correct prediction.
candidates.key_layers: Takes lead at L28, surges L29-33 (26%→88%)
key_evidence: F33:324 (MLP, 110.9 proj) — dominant Q-specific prediction channel in final layer
N32:3894 (+1.38 proj) — strongest MLP writer, votes purely for Q
F30:7134 (attn, 48.4 proj) — early decision-phase Q channel activation
N29:754 (+0.70 proj) — Q/E writer with Q preference, activates at decision onset

candidates.narrative: E emerges as the primary competitor in late decision layers, peaking at 11.1% at L30 before fading to 4.9%. E benefits from chemical similarity to Q (both polar with side-chain amide/carboxyl groups) and shares some prediction channels (N30:2153 votes +0.84 for E, +0.75 for Q). However, E-specific features are weaker and E loses ground in final layers as Q-specific channels dominate. The competition suggests the model briefly considers the charged variant before committing to the uncharged amide.
key_evidence: N30:2153 (+0.75 Q, +0.84 E) — shared polar prediction channel, slight E preference
Peak at L30 coincides with attention-driven boost (+3.22 attn delta)
Suppressed in final layers by Q-specific MLP neurons

candidates.narrative: L shows strong logit-lens probability early (13.7% at L0, peaks at 17.8% at L26) but this reflects the representation's initial hydrophobic-leaning character from reading local sequence context (IFVKT neighbors), not a model prediction. L is a hydrophobic residue inappropriate for the N-terminal exposed position. As the model refines its representation through layers 10-23 to encode polar/charged character, L's logit-lens projection fluctuates but never reflects genuine consideration. L collapses in the decision phase (4.5% at L29, 1.4% at L33) as polar-specific prediction channels activate.
key_evidence: L0 logit lens at 13.7% reflects hydrophobic bias from local sequence IFVKT
Peak at L26 (17.8%) coincides with representation refinement, not commitment
Suppressed by polar-encoding features through perception phase

candidates.narrative: K dominates the logit lens through the late perception phase, leading from L14-L25 and peaking at 31.2% at L23. This reflects the representation's encoding of charged/polar N-terminal context rather than a prediction—K is chemically appropriate (charged, polar) but not the specific answer. K benefits from features encoding positive charge compatibility (N25:4987 votes +0.79 for K, +0.71 for Q) but lacks the specific prediction channels that activate for Q in L28+. K fades rapidly in the decision phase as Q-specific neurons fire.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L14-L25 (peaks 31.2% at L23), fades L26+
key_evidence: L23 peak at 31.2% represents refined polar/charged representation, not prediction
N25:4987 (+0.79 K, +0.71 Q) shows K/Q chemical similarity in early decision
Lacks late-layer Q-specific channels, drops to 1.4% by L33

candidates.narrative: N appears prominently in the logit lens at L17 (15.3%) and L29 (12.0%), reflecting the representation's polar character. As a small polar residue chemically similar to Q (both have amide side chains), N's logit-lens presence indicates the model has correctly identified the polar/amide character of this position. However, N lacks the specific prediction support that Q receives—no high-projection N-specific features activate in decision layers. N's trajectory shows the model distinguishing between general polar/amide character (which N shares with Q) and the specific Q identity.
key_evidence: L17 peak reflects polar/amide representation character
Chemical similarity to Q (both polar with amide groups) explains logit-lens correlation
Lacks decision-phase prediction channels, drops to 1.1% by L33

turning_points.description: Early perception phase shows extreme volatility with 7 lead changes as the model refines its representation of N-terminal context. The logit lens cycles through S→H→N→A→S→A→K, reflecting the accumulation of different contextual features rather than prediction attempts. Features like F1:5480 and F9:5728 (40+ projection) encode positional and structural context. The representation shifts from initial hydrophobic bias (L at 13.7% from local sequence) toward polar/charged character as N-terminal position encoding dominates.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. L23 shows K leading at 31.2% with the representation fully encoding polar/charged N-terminal context. L24 brings the first decision-phase features (F24:6298 at 19.3 projection, F24:217 at 16.7) and MLP neurons begin AA-specific voting, though net projection remains slightly negative (-0.3). L25 activates early Q-preferring neurons (N25:4987 at +0.71 for Q) and attention heads write strongly (+2.45 from L25 H16). The representation transitions from 'this is a polar/charged N-terminal position' to 'Q specifically belongs here.'

Q's decisive surge. L28 marks Q's first lead (17.8%, overtaking L at 17.5%) driven by local attention writing (+1.96 from L28 H2). L29 shows massive MLP activity with strong Q writers (N29:3536 +0.81, N29:754 +0.70) despite net negative projection from competing erasers. L30-L33 activate the highest-specificity Q prediction channels: F30:7134 (48.4 attn), F33:324 (110.9 MLP—the dominant feature), and N32:3894 (+1.38 pure Q vote). Q rises from 26% to 88% while E peaks at 11% then fades. The final layers show both attention and MLP streams converging on Q with high confidence.

deep_dives.label: N-terminal position features L1-L9
deep_dives.caption: Early features encode the N-terminal positional context. F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 (44+ projection) fire strongly to mark this as the second position after the start methionine. F9:5728 (46.8 projection) continues this encoding. These features establish the structural and positional constraints that will guide later prediction.

deep_dives.label: Representation refinement L10-L23
deep_dives.caption: Watch the logit lens cycle through S, A, K, T as the model refines its representation of polar/charged N-terminal context. Key velocity events at L12 (-3.63 attn-driven), L17 (-3.08 attn-driven), and L23 (-3.53 attn-driven) show the model actively reshaping the representation. This is context assembly, not prediction—the model is encoding 'what kind of residue' not 'which specific residue.'

deep_dives.label: Perception→Decision L23-L25
deep_dives.caption: Layer 24 features mark the transition from context encoding to prediction. F24:6298 (19.3 projection) and F24:217 (16.7 projection) are the first decision-phase features to activate. Compare these to L18 features (all under 12 projection)—the model shifts from assembling a representation to committing to an answer.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision neurons L29-L32
deep_dives.caption: The MLP stream drives Q's final surge. L29 shows strong Q writers (N29:3536 +0.81, N29:754 +0.70) fighting against general erasers (net -5.39). L30 provides +4.13 net support with N30:2153 and N30:4022. L32 features the decisive N32:3894 (+1.38 projection, pure Q vote). Watch how Q-specific neurons overcome competing signals to secure the prediction.

deep_dives.label: Q-specific prediction channels L30-L33
deep_dives.caption: The highest-specificity Q prediction features activate in final layers. F30:7134 (48.4 projection, attention) initiates the Q surge. F33:324 (110.9 projection, MLP) is the single strongest feature in the entire forward pass, providing decisive Q support. F33:4166, F33:6423, F33:9048 (80+ projection each) form a converging set of Q-specific channels that lock in the 88% confidence prediction.

deep_dives.label: Local sequence integration L25-L31
deep_dives.caption: Key attention heads integrate local sequence context M[Q]IFVKT. L25 H16 writes +2.45 projection with 96% local attention. L28 H2 writes +1.96 with 93% local attention, triggering Q's first lead. L31 H6 erases -2.72 with 95% local attention, refining the final representation. These heads read the immediate neighbors to constrain the prediction.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts Q by assembling a representation of N-terminal exposed polar context through layers 1-23, then activating Q-specific prediction channels in layers 28-33. The strongest evidence comes from the convergence of high-specificity features in final layers: F33:324 (110.9 projection, MLP), N32:3894 (+1.38 pure Q vote), and F30:7134 (48.4 projection, attention). The early logit-lens volatility (cycling through S, K, N, A) reflected the model's refinement of what kind of residue belongs at position 2—polar, charged, N-terminal appropriate—rather than premature guessing. Once the context was fully assembled by L23, Q-specific prediction neurons fired decisively, distinguishing Q from chemically similar candidates (E, N, K) and driving confidence from 7% to 88% in just 5 layers.
